Introduction

A facility that uses or stores more than a threshold quantity of a regulated substance is required to submit a

Risk Management Program (RMP) to the United States Environmental Protection Agency (USEPA). An RMP comprises several elements, including an evaluation of potential accident scenarios and a comprehensive program to prevent accidental releases of regulated chemicals.



The RMP summarizes the management, administrative, procedural, and technological controls that the facility uses in combination to minimize the risk of hazardous chemical releases to the surrounding community. The RMP includes the following information:

- Introduction;

- Facility identification, regulated substances, and covered processes;

- Policies to protect health, environment, and safety;

- Hazard Assessment;

- Prevention Program;

- Five-Year Accident History;

- Emergency Response Plan; and

- Planned Changes to improve safety



Kinder Morgan Liquids Terminals (KMLT) Chicago terminal, located south of the city within the Illinois International Port District, stores a material containing n-pentane in an amount greater than the threshold of 10,000 pounds.



Facility Identification and Regulated Substances

The KMLT Chicago Terminal is a public "for-hire" bulk liquid storage terminal, approximately 178 acres in area and located approximately 19 miles south of Chicago, Illinois. The terminal is bounded by the Calumet River to the west and south, and the Illinois International Port on the north and east. Chicago Fire Department Engine 80 is located within 6 miles of the facility. The terminal provides tank storage for liquid chemicals, food grade products, and deicer products on a "contract" basis. Presently, approximately 86 permitted aboveground storage tanks are available (approximately 32,000,000-gallon capacity) for storage and distribution of customer products or for support activities. Materials are received at the terminal by tank trucks, rail cars, barge, and p
